        "statement": "Consider the arithmetic progression defined by 10k + 7 for k in N. We aim to show that this progression contains infinitely many primes."
      },
      {
        "type": "assumption",
        "statement": "Assume there were only finitely many such primes, say p1, p2, ..., pn."
      },
      {
        "type": "let",
        "variable": "N",
        "value": "10(p1p2...pn) - 3",
        "existence": [
          {
            "type": "observation",
            "statement": "By construction, N ends in 7, fitting the form of numbers we are considering."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "observation",
        "statement": "N cannot be divisible by any of the primes p1, p2, ..., pn. For any pi, N + 3 = 10(p1p2...pn) is divisible by pi, but N leaves a remainder of 3 when divided by pi, not zero."
      },
      {
        "type": "observation",
        "statement": "Since N is not divisible by any pi, and since it is greater than 1 and ends in 7, it must have a prime factor that is not in our initial list and similarly ends in 7. This contradicts our assumption of having listed all such primes."
      },
      {
        "type": "conclusion",
        "statement": "By contradiction, there must be infinitely many primes that end in the digit 7."
      }
    ]
  }
]
